"Coaching Lab" is a training course organized by NGO Life Zone, which will take place in Parnu, Estonia 17-25th of May, 2015, and will bring together 24 participants from 12 countries. The training course is specially designed for youth workers interested in coaching and using the coaching methods in the work of their organizations.

Coaching as a training or development process  via which individual is supported while achieving a specific personal or professional competence result or goal is an important component of effective functioning of NGO as a support for young people. Individual work with using the coaching methods inside the organization, as well as work with local communities, can increase the quality of NGOs' work generally and have direct influence on the target groups organizations work with.

At the same time, we face a problem that youth workers representing NGOs which work for local communities have lack of coaching skills in their work. First of all, it is caused by the reason that youth workers are not aware about importance of these coaching skills. And as a result, they are not able to use in their work. Moreover, it is caused by lack of professional coaches and coaching trainers which are ready to share their knowledge and experience with youth workers, which in a way comes from lack of proper non-formal education, missing international cooperation in this field and supporting system between NGOs around Europe. 

The objectives of this training course are: 
- To learn about importance of coaching skills in youth work;
- To learn coaching skills how to use different techniques and methods in individual coaching in order to guide and mentor volunteers knowing more methods and techniques.;
- To practice different coaching techniques and methods;
- To increase the quality of NGOs' work in local communities and inside their own organizations;
- To establish partner relationships between organizations and create the support system;
- To learn about opportunities for young people and youth organizations in frame of Erasmus+ Programme;
- To plan the activities for future cooperation between the organizations.

The participants will be empowered to learn from their own experience and create their own individual knowledge and development concerned with issue. We call it “learning by doing”. This is the method, based on experiential learning. In this approach learning becomes a specific and individual process, because it depends from the person, her/his behavior, reaction and emotions, attitude and way of thinking. 

The main methods of working will be exercises, games and activities, in which participants will experience the models of real life. We will also develop together minimum standards/criteria for what a hosting and sending organization needs to fulfill. 

On a personal level the result of the training can be that the participants will identify and show up all their core qualities and will be able to perform all different approaches available, through their own unique style. Additionally to this, a result can be a long lasting confidence, while interacting with others, which will bring them to their desired outcomes with much less effort than before. 

The organizational results of the training can be that we start an active coaching process in the partner organizations, and start build a strong platform of organizations, that operate based on same standards, values and understanding. Another result would be joining forces and applying together for further projects, to look for possibilities to cooperate with each other in the future.

Over the past 20 years, the technical and vocational education has been subject to numerous reforms and changes that had weakened the training offer. Add to this the phenomenon of widespread Italic "genericism" that, pushing students towards a choice of extensive and generic studies, is actually the main reason of demotivation towards studies and school drop-out.

These elements move in contrast with the needs of the labor market for technical-professional and in particular in tourism and hotel sector.

Similarly, the demand for labor, in conjunction with the technological development and competitiveness of the market, requires increasingly specific skills and the same employers recognize that the preparation of the staff coming out of the training course is not always adequate.

To complete the picture, it is estimated that in the near future, at the conclusion of the current economic crisis, the demand for labor will greatly increase, with particular reference to its technical and professional fields

In this context the institutes IFOM, Varalli, Bertarelli and Besta have found the common need to compensate the mismatch between training offer and the needs of enterprises, reducing the mismatch between demand and supply of labor, reduce early school leaving and improving integration between schools and business.
 
The realization of this general objective goes through the achievement of the following specific objectives:

- For students, to strengthen their professional skills, transversal and personal, enhancing their career prospects and their motivation, creating a sense of entrepreneurship, emancipation, European and intercultural awareness;

- For the staff involved, to improve their professional and linguistic skills, to understand the practices related to the world of education and its links with the world of work, to understand the social, linguistic and cultural differences, to increase the ability to address the needs of the most disadvantaged and to strengthen the capacity to sustain their motivation to work;

- For the organizations involved, to learn to operate internationally, to understand how to provide the most stimulating educational activities, to create a modern and dynamic working environment, to develop activities good for the whole civil society.
 
For this reason, the project "Learning in hospitality Europe by undergoing a traineeship VET" promotes the development of internships abroad for students of the consortium schools.

 The project includes two activities:
1) Mobility of 92 students and 16 escorts for an internship abroad lasting one month;
2) Mobility of 20 neo-graduates for an internship abroad lasting 10 weeks
The activities will take place from 01.06.2017 until 31.01.2019 and includes the selection and preparation of students, the organization of the mobilities, activities abroad, evaluations, dissemination and follow-up activities.
The consortium plans to include in mobility 8 students with special needs, in detail students with DSA or BES.

The impact of the proposed actions will be wide and will involve multiple levels of recipients in direct and indirect manner:

students:
- Competitiveness on the labor market;
- Improving their social skills;
- The acquisition of transversal skills (self-esteem, responsibility, ability to take tasks, ...) will also bring benefits to emancipation and employability;
- Peers of the students are indirect beneficiaries, through the experiences of the participants in the action.

Teachers:
- The renewed interest in teaching will bring greater efficiency in learning of the students;
- Sharing a common experience with the students will produce a greater understanding of their difficulties and more effective communication between teachers and students;
- A better understanding of the labor market in Europe will offer more precise knowledge in supporting the education of students.

Schools:
- Increased ability to manage projects;
- Increased understanding of the training gaps of students who are entering the world of work;
- Development of ECVET as tools for the recognition and validation of students' Learning Outcomes;
- Increased understanding of the tourist business processes in Europe;
- Increased ability to intervene on motivation and orientation of students, particularly those with fewer opportunities;
- Increased competitiveness of vocational schools, compared to other training institutions, crediting the institutions involved at the local level;
- Refinement of the offer of training based on the skills and specific needs of the students, thanks to new contacts with foreign companies;
- Training of students in line with market requirements;
- Increased internationalization of training institutions, in line with European standards of education.

 During the project, the Europe Direct Regione Lombardia will disseminate the project among citizens, schoold and local companies.

The overall aim of TNT is to create a deeper understanding of the civil society actors and the role we have in our nations and be able to approach it with non-violent communication techniques. To approach this topic we will start with exploring the meaning of the words conflict, youth movement, peace etc. and at the same time we will follow like an itinerary from social movements for democracy and justice, movements against discrimination and racism and we will explore present developments in the different European regions regions, movements born during the economical crisis in Europe and other important actors around the world and especially Europe. 

First of all, we understand integration a political dimension on youth work not only about awareness of Rights and Duties, but also a matter of Participation, Responsibility and Sense of Belonging of young people in various level from Local, National, European and Global societies. Therefore the competence of the youth worker/leader to be active in those measures are quite relevant as it’s the core base for the activism. It focus on Integrating a political dimension into the youth’ work competences and it mean an overall system of values, attitudes and beliefs, as well as skills and knowledge which can be put into practice to manage diverse complex situations and tasks successfully. Self-confidence, motivation and well-being are important pre-requisites for a young person to be able to act out his/her developed competences.
In practical it allows the youth worker to:
• Connecting [youth] policies and educational programmes in their work youth young people;
• Integrating political values and beliefs which reflect on their personal political values and beliefs in the course and to act in a responsible and constructive manner
• Supporting young people in developing political thinking
• Applying democracy and human rights principles

The training will give competence and methods to participants to analyse the social conflicts, will teach them how to act wisely, and being active leaders in the civil society.

In our complex Europe there are a lot of civil actors, agendas, meetings, and factors that have impacts on how political decisions are taken and how the policies are developing. The awareness of these is not always easy to understand by young people nowadays. Therefore, in order to tackle the issue we wish to make the following objectives:
• Give to participants the tools and competences to understand what civil society is and what is its role in our own societies; 
• Familiarize the participants with concepts and approaches of non violent actions i.e. how to use it best and adapt it to local contexts and realities in order to promote peace building;
• Equip the participants with skills to act in order to fulfill their goals;  
• Empower the young people to act wisely in conflicts on individual as well as societal levels;
• Review and enhance participants’ competences (knowledge, skills, attitudes) in working as  multipliers, and activists on peace building using non formal education tools;
• Enable participants to develop activities and campaigns for multipliers in conflict transformation and non-violent actions, at international, national or local level.

The project will include 30 youth workers/leaders from 13 programme countries for 8 days (including travel days) in Austria. Methodology of the training will be based in non formal education and its holistic approach. Participants will improve their competencies through non formal methods like brainstorming, group works, simulation, role play, open group discussion, open space for reflection and other methods that trainers will adapt based in the needs of participants. 

Participants will gain new tools and ways to use non-violent communication and how to use that when integrating their youth groups and individuals into political dimension on their communities. A set of techniques, theory, mentoring support and examples will be available for the participants and showed how they can adapt and recreate that back in their own communities taking in account their own realities and needs. Participants will also have the opportunities to be more aware and to point out those issues when they will be back home and be able to decode the messages from the media and other populist campaigns.

This training is is designed to have a high level dissemination. Project that we are planning by us hopefully will continue in a series events about non-violent actions and political integration by young people. 

The impact on the participants will be measured by the following activities made by them and also the number of people involved. According our expectation we would develop at least 24 follow up activities where each of them would involve at least around 20 participants, which leads to a minimum number of 480 young people receiving a direct impact of the training besides the participants themselves.

From last decades Europe is facing two phenomenon that is changing all societies from its habits, cultures and background. Together with that change in the identity of the society, young people are facing more than never huge obstacles to enter the job market in an effective and sustainable way. Young people’s experiences of employment are at present, and have been for a decade or so, characterized by precariousness, a hollowing out of opportunity for quality employment, a lengthening yo-yo trajectory in and out of short-term work, unemployment and training or education. 
In the same time young people are more open to work with diverse communities and have a huge potential to improve their competences and integrate themselves into a constant dynamic World. That reality opens some questions: How is possible that we have more capable young people and their employment rates continue so low? What are the new competences that can improve young people chance on labor market? How youth creativity can be a major tool for that integration?

“CRE-ACTIVE” is a training course, which was developed as a module for youth workers/trainers to help them to answer their questions concerning the Creativity to support Employment. We will approach the idea of creativity on different levels and the self-assessment of the new competences that improves the chance of young people in the labour market composed by a huge diversity of cultures, traditions and habit in the European context. We will work on case, examples and Creativity in practice. Together, we will be working on improving their competences and how to motivate young people to use their creativity for a sustainable and desirable work placement.

“CRE-ACTIVE”  is a training course that aims to support the professional development of young people and to raise awareness of the new competences concerning a Diverse Europe. 
The main objectives for the training course is following:

- To discuss the issue of youth unemployment in various European countries;
- To give youth workers tools for career assistance of young people;
- To practice tools and methods of career counseling;
- To create space for sharing experience in working with young people;
- To practice effective tools of fostering creative approaches and positive attitudes towards job search;
- To foster mutual understanding amongst youth workers from various European countries regarding their role in youth's career choice;
- To contribute to the creation of support systems for young people;
- To empower and develop youth workers/youth leaders being competent in the field of assisting youngsters in the labor market. 

The activities consists of a six days intensive training course, including aims, description and methods used. (See attached "CRE-ACTIVE" programme). 
Methodology of the training will be based on non-formal education and its holistic approach. Participants will improve their competencies through non-formal methods like brainstorming, group works, simulation, role play, open group discussion, open space for reflection and other methods that trainers will adapt based in the needs of participants.
